Save on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than a thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, which have developed mainly due to the improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the head of the department of the National Epidemiology Center.
It is also used in many places on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatological department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
A man who was admitted to the hospital after a serious accident was shown to be resistant to antibiotics.
The patient was separated.
A similar infection occurred at the beginning of the year.
He was discharged from the hospital in a serious car accident, but soon after he had to return with MRSA infection, and has not been able to perform an important operation since then due to the bacteria in his body.
This year, up to December 10, 1094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Böröcz Karolina, chief class physician at the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, others are unknown.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, which is Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria is carried by one-third of people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be cured well.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or incorrectly, a bacteria that reacts well to antibiotics develops a very resistant bacteria against antibiotics, which spreads rapidly under inadequate hospital conditions.
First of all, when the immune system is temporarily or permanently malfunctioning, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis - in patients with the most impaired body, the elderly or low body weight.
According to the director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the carriage, MRSA is just not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We separate such patients, the nursing staff provides the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and they have the right antibiotics for their treatment," Tibor Nyulasi said.
Patients who enter the hospital are initially examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not always possible to avoid infection.
It's not fashion for sampling
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA would be preventable, but the current domestic hospital conditions and conditions do not favour the prevention of the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Böröcz Karolina.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals, nursing homes, hospitals should monitor the patients who are recovering, and patients carrying MRSA should be isolated immediately.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not in fashion.
It also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies.
Most cases are thus brought to light when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief of the department at the epidemiological center.
The European Union has stringent recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections and diseases.
It should be sought to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out so that resistance to drugs does not develop, but hospitals do not adhere to this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in pathological and basic care, said Böröcz Karolina.
Save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is most often spread from one patient to another through the mediation of health care personnel.
Therefore, the use of handwashing, gloves and masks plays a very important role, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals.
With MRSA infection, it spreads through contact, but in domestic hospital conditions, it is not always possible to separate the infected patient.
In addition, the hospital rooms are often crowded, often very close to the beds, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, it is also perceptible, noted Böröcz Karolina, that hospitals in an unfavourable financial situation save on disinfectants, there is little caregiver, many patients, so there is an even greater chance of developing infections.
According to Böröcz Karolina, where appropriate precautions are followed, there is less evidence of such an infection, or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is causing huge expenses for health insurers, which is why they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government programme included the prevention or reduction of MRSA.
According to the signs, the program is successful, based on the reported data, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
Among the priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) is the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
