Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard raised the country’s risk
With the support of Jobbik Movement for Hungary, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August of this year, raised the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division.
In the company's "risk warning" it was written: in relation to the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that the "possibility of evaluating the ethnic tensions between the gypsies and non-gypsies in Hungary may, by the way, be short-lived".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an act - added the research institute.
As they wrote, all this is due to one of the main failures of Hungarian political actors: "the public debate on the Roma issue was handed over to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy against this gypsies."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens the extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts, they believe.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, under the influence of the great domestic and international media surveillance, "significantly spoiled the image of Hungary created abroad, especially in terms of the stability of the country and the belief in the democratic development of the country".
It is recalled that the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has gained increasing publicity and momentum since the fall of 2006, is part of the reorganization of more self-defense organizations called "national self-defense" in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
"The common feature of these consolidations is that they define themselves as a civil organization, while openly proclaiming the preparation of their members - whether armed - for defensive tasks (catastrophe protection, national defense, police protection), in addition to the duty of the police, the army, or the state."
It was noted that all this is done in accordance with the method which, based on the political and impartiality of society, seeks to put different political aspirations into civilian clothing.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association is therefore not only used to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration in these associations, but also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-intensive factor in terms of neighbouring relations.
"In recent months, several neighbouring states have also referred to the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of danger, and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to prove their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, so political risks for the whole region have increased.
As it has been written, the operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, the establishment of which was announced in August 2007 by the Bulgarian National Union on the far right (BNU).
Against the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard are the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of the districts of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this decision to set up the Guard, saying that the organization was aimed at "national self-defense".
For the past 17 years, Bulgaria has experienced “gypsy terror”, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, according to the Political Capital.
It added: the initiative sparked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As it was written, the increased risk of ethnic clashes indicates that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they are setting up their own guard as resistance.
Since the operation of the Hungarian Guard so far shows similarities with the operation of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that the Hungarian Roma react in the same way by organising their own self-defense to the threat.
Juh<0xC3><0xA1>sz Attila, director of research at Political Capital, told the televised office that risk analysis was one of the activities of the research institute.
As he said, they publish their risk analysis every year, and if they experience one that could affect the change in risk, they inform the public, as in this case, by issuing a risk warning.
