In Hungary, the law accurately marks the red-letter days, and the reorganization of the working day around the holidays has become a general practice, which will be less for next year.
In the US and the EU, the holiday is not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between a national and a state holiday and a working day.
Working days are usually linked to ecclesiastical holidays and significant historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the year and the first day of the new - the latter only so that the New Year's guests can relax.
There are a total of 11 red-letter festivals throughout the year.
The National Day commemorates the Revolution of 1848, the 15th of March and the 23rd of October, the anniversary of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1, we celebrate the work, and on November 1 and 2, we remember our relatives, our friends.
In addition, there is a two-day celebration of Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our public, national or even religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to relocate the working day in cases where we would only work for one day before or after the red letter holiday.
